{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505272"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2425"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2425"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.04,0.34,0.11,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48149"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2425"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33022"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"961"},{"type":"tags","id":"1660"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48149"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a ten-day history of passing frothy, cloudy urine. Upon further questioning, she also describes passing streams of urine interrupted by \u0022bubbling\u0022. Her medical history includes a hysterectomy when she was aged 40 and a pyelolithotomy when she was aged 68. Her only other recent medical history included an episode of left-sided lower abdominal pain two months ago which lasted about five days and then settled of its own accord. She takes no regular medications. On physical examination she appear well with vitals within normal limits. Abdominal examination demonstrates no abnormalities. A urine sample is collected and sent for microscopy and culture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT urogram","Colonoscopy","CT abdomen","Cystoscopy","Pelvic ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient is describing pneumaturia indicated by symptoms of frothy, cloudy urine, interrupted urine stream and bubbling. Of the various potential causes of gas in the urine, the commonest is an enterovesical fistula. Of the many possible causes of fistulous communication between the gut and the bladder, the commonest is diverticular disease. This would be the most likely explanation in this case, particularly as the patient had an episode of undiagnosed pain preceding these symptoms, which could have been diverticulitis. The best investigation for pneumaturia and suspected enterovesical fistula is a CT abdomen. Gas within the bladder is suggestive of a fistula and further direct visualisation will be required to determine the cause. The CT is likely to identify any mass lesion adjacent to the bladder (eg diverticular or tumour mass).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT urogram\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful investigation for visualisation of the urinary tract including collecting systems, ureters and bladder. This is especially helpful in diagnosing cancers of the bladder but not fistulas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may show a cause of enterovesical fistula such as a diverticular disease but is less useful in assessing the full extent of the disease and path of the fistula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E allows direct visualisation of the bladder and biopsy of a lesion but does not identify extraluminal content.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic ultrasounds\u003C/strong\u003E do not provide detailed anatomical information regarding the complexity of a fistula.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pneumaturia is best investigated with a CT abdomen."],"references":["Golabek T, Szymanska A, Szopinski T, Bukowczan J, Furmanek M, Powroznik J et al. Enterovesical Fistulae: Aetiology, Imaging, and Management. Gastroenterol Res Pract. 2013;10:1155. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3857900/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33022"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2425"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33022"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-07T16:23:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-07T16:23:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48149"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"create